                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d621">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-18T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >April 18, 1936—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 18—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>212. Your 123, April 11, 2 p.m. In the absence of Atherton, substance of the
                    Department’s views was communicated informally to Orde yesterday by
                        Johnson.<note n="96" xml:id="d621fn96">Herschel V. Johnson, First Secretary
                        of Embassy in the United Kingdom.</note> Orde made no comment except to say
                    that they were still waiting for advices from the Treasury in the matter and he
                    reiterated that it was not Leith-Ross who was conducting the negotiations, that
                    Leith-Ross had only given advice.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
